 shew a gradual improvement\nvvae; expressed in a business review\nu-.-.tied by the United States Chamber\nf Commerce Prepared by Archer\nWall Douglas, chairman of the\nchr.mbei's committee on statistics\nj'.wl etarrhrds, the review stated:\n'The most convincing evidence that\na re on the high road to recovery\ni is found in the universal report from\ntciy section of the country of the\nj stcnclMy growing sentiment that\nbusiness will be better in the spring.\nI Th? review predicted there would\nnet be a sudden return to prosperity\nj but a 'slow and natural working out\nj c f these processes of liquidation\nI which are now in full operation.'\nj I.:- another statement i:;sued by the\nj Chamber of Commerce to-day Joseph\nj P. Defrccs its president urged pass\nl -gv by ccngiess 0f the budget bill. It\nMa ill be impossible under the present\nwasteful appir.pl iaticin system, Mr\nDefrccs said, to bring about the eco\ninomy and efficiency in public busi\n!ress which he said the country was\ni demanding-\nDAN FITCH'S BIG MINSTREL\nSHOW HUB THURSDAY\nAPARTMENTS AND BABIES\nSpringfield Republican.\nA Pittsburgh landlord whose\" name\nmay be hailed by generations yet!\nunborn, is J. L- Mc.Caskey, owner of\nthe Cappalpa apartments. He nas\nannounced that t\".e first baby born\nthere will bring to its parents a\nmonth's rent free. lie has dared, that\nis, to make babies welcome in a\ndwelling of the sort reserved by the\nstern custom cf his kind for the un\nmarried, the childless and the wid\now ed, who are free of the 'incum\nbrance' by which the earth is replen\nished. The revolutionary possibilities\nof the innovation challenge the im\nagination. VVihy should there pot be apart\nment houses constructed and main\ntained for people who wish to raise\nfamilies and who do not .wish to take\nup their residence in a subui'ban or\na run-down city district Is there\nany reason why the best appointed\naparment blocks in the mose desir\nable locations should be monuments\nto a vanishinp- birth rate? Not all\nof them ere; seme of them may\nproperly for one reason or another\nbe taboo for children. But Mr. Mc\nCaskey's announcement suggests that\nmany of them, and with profit to\ntheir owners, might actually encour\nage the coming of children.\nThe model apartment house with\nsuch a purpose would be different\nfrom the typical apartment house of\ntoday. It would have nurseries and\nplayrooms; it would have roof gar\ndens with their swings and sand pil\nes and fresh air and sunshine; it\nwould have elevators that would ac\ncomodate baby carriages ad peram\nbulators, and downstairs ball space\nto park them in; it would have pur\nses with whom for a consideration a\nmother might leave a youngster on\nnecessary occasions. Perhaps it would\nhave sound-proof wails- It would have\nether features which would readily\nsuggest themselves to the enterpris\ning landlord and his specializing ar\nchitect. And why shouldn't such an apart\nment pay? Its rents would have to\ncorrespond to the costs, but why\nwouldn't manv parents be willing\nand glad to get such accommodatios\nAny kind of buUding anywhere comes,\nhigh just now, but as opportunity\nopens up to supply actual needs, the\nactuality of this need deserves a\nheaTiing. There would b a social con\neien\"e in the enterprise and there\nought to be the landlord's legitimate\nprofit as well\nAmonir lawyers in Ohio who\nknow Mr. Daughtery's standing at\nthe bar, we hear that there is some\nthing like consternation at the\nthought of his becoming- Attorney\nGeneral of the United States. New\nYork Times.\nTOrcii..M.\nf4 'J\nMS\nGi\n.in.\nit\naranteed to outwear Leather. Makes\nas nice job and is waterproof. I have\n\"\"all kinds of Shoes.\nIn announcing the comine- of the\ni Dan Fitch minstrel, company for\n7bui':c!a; Friday and Saturday of\nj this week, the management cf the\n(have been playing the largest cities\nIff the south for several seasons. No\nbetter proof of their capabilities and\ni popularity may 